I really wanted this place to be good. It’s such a cute café with a great location downtown. The atmosphere is really nice. But as soon as you enter there is a cold vibe from the staff. The service is hardly what one might cal “friendly.”  The prices aren’t bad at first glance, but when the food comes you can’t help but to feel cheated. Portion sizes are small, and the presentation is bland. I ordered scrambled eggs as well as an egg white omelet. That’s literally all that I got. At least they’re honest.  No seasoning. Bland. The egg whites were overcooked. It was hardly an omelette at all. Toast on the side. Perhaps it was buttered but I couldn’t tell... it was so dry.  And the side salad was literally just a handful of greens. No additions, spices, flavor, or garnish whatsoever.  I wish it had turned out better. But I probably won’t return. There are plenty of cafes in the city. This one has a great atmosphere. But if you’re looking for anything near flavorful food or decent service, your best head somewhere else. Once again I’m left regretting that I didn’t go to McDonald’s. At least they’re tasty and consistent.

This is my number one choice for catering business lunches and dinners. They have a wide variety of selection whether it be wraps or sandwiches. Their pastries are d.e.l.i.c.i.o.u.s. Their catering manager, Kathleen Gallo, and Chef Richard provide Number One service. They're always available and happy to attend to our "all of a sudden" requests no matter the size. This is an exquisite choice. Thank you for the almost 20 years in the Financial District. Kudos!

There's something about the cakes here that just has me hooked. The one with fruitiness, like raspberry/passionfruit/blueberry, are just so delicious. I like that they're lighter than most of the cakes you can get elsewhere, which are sometimes just overly rich and creamy. Financier just makes cakes with really balanced flavor profiles, that you take one bite of and can just keep on eating. A little pricey but worth every bit of the price for special occasions. My family is hooked and we keep buying these whenever we celebrate a birthday.

Really cute shop! I went in for pastries for the holidays and I was surprised by how cute the yule log cake was.  I purchased a chocolate chip cookie, the tiny chocolate mousse cake, and the tiny modern yule log. The chocolate chip cookie is hard on the edges but soft towards the center. It can be a tad sweet, but I can see how people would like to order coffee or tea with it. The mousse cake is the perfect flavor of chocolate. It's not too sweet or too bitter and it's a strong chocolate flavor. The modern yule log is made from pistachios, chocolate, and I think cherry? It's cute because it has two tiny mushroom-shaped meringues on it which makes it look more "log-like". There were macaroon shells on the end of the logs and they were surprisingly really good. I would definitely go back for more cakes or macaroons.
Financier has great pastries and cakes - croissants, macarons and light meals. Good spot for a casual coffee or tea and a cake.

First of all prepare yourself for the prices, but remember it's the financial district of New York so $4 for a small coffee is still probably on the cheap side.  Secondly the pastries are absolutely to die for and I would gladly pay $4.50 over and over again for another chocolate mousse cake because it was absolutely delicious!  I think I paid around $8 total for the pastry and a small hot chocolate but the hot chocolate was definitely made from scratch and not a powder or mix so it was well worth it.  If you're from out of town and looking for a quick coffee and snack maybe pass this place by.  But if you've got a little money to spend then I highly recommend this place.  My only sadness comes from the fact that I live in Wisconsin and can't get the chocolate mousse cake again for a long long time.  :(
